Step 3a — Rename the action first
Top-bar "..." on the new Condition → Rename:
BP Manual Override
Step 3b — Left value (use fx / expression mode)
Click into the left field of the condition, switch to fx (expression editor). Paste:
coalesce(first(outputs('Get_BP_After_Upsert')?['body/value'])?['pei_owningbumanual'], false)
What this does:

outputs('Get_BP_After_Upsert')?['body/value'] — the array returned by List rows
first(...) — pull the single row (we set Row count = 1)
?['pei_owningbumanual'] — read the override flag from that row
coalesce(..., false) — treat null/missing as false. This matters for legacy BPs created before today's schema change (they don't have the field set yet)

Step 3c — Operator
is equal to
Step 3d — Right value — CRITICAL: use fx / expression mode
Click into the right field, switch to fx, paste:
true
Why fx not text: typing true as plain text creates the string "true". Yes/No fields evaluate as boolean true / false at runtime. String-vs-boolean comparison always returns false. The fx mode makes it a boolean literal.
Step 3e — Save
Save the flow.

Internal-name watch
If the left expression errors with something like "cannot find action Get_BP_After_Upsert", the action's internal name doesn't match its display name. To check:

Click on Get BP After Upsert action header
Click the "..." menu → Settings
Look for the action ID / internal name shown there

If it's something else like List_rows_5 or Get_BP_After_Upsert_2, replace Get_BP_After_Upsert in the expression with that exact internal name (underscores replace spaces).
Same issue we hit on the filter expression for C2 — Power Automate internal names follow rename history, not always the current display name.

